<node id="article:2000_164">
  <data key="d0">Article</data>
  <data key="d2">Hybrid Systems: State of the Art and Perspectives</data>
  <data key="d3"></data>
  <data key="d4">This short pap er pro vides a brief o v erview of the con ten t of the plenary lecture on h ybrid systems. Key references are also listed. Key W ords| h ybrid systems; v eri cation; sup ervisory con trol; appro ximation; reac habilit y .   In tro duction Hybrid systems are dynamic systems with b oth discrete-v alued and con tin uous-v alued state v ari- ables. Recen t in terest in h ybrid systems has b een stim ulated b y sev eral factors. F or con trol the- orists, there is the in tellectual c hallenge of ex- tending fundamen tal concepts suc h as stabilit y and con trollabilit y to the h ybrid system con text. Computer scien tists, on the other hand, are in- terested in extending formal metho ds for dealing with discrete-state systems to include con tin uous- state dynamics. F rom b oth p ersp ectiv es, the con- trol of ph ysical dynamic systems using comput- ers pro vides the principal set of p oten tial applica- tions. The ob jectiv e of this plenary presen tation is to pro vide an o v erview of ma jor themes in h y- brid system researc h during the past ten y ears, and to o er some p ersp ectiv e on the imp ortan t directions for future researc h. This brief pa- p er giv es a summary of the topics co v ered in the plenary session along with citations to some k ey references in the literature. F or general bac kground, the reader is encouraged to lo ok through some of the recen t sp ecial issues of jour- nals and series of conference and w orkshop pro- ceedings dev oted to h ybrid systems (Sp e cial Is- sue on Hybrid Systems,    ; Sp e cial Issue on Hy- brid Systems,    ; A Sp e cial Issue on Hybrid Sys- tems,   ; Sp e cial Issue on Hybrid Contr ol Sys- tems,   ; Hybrid Systems,    ; Hybrid Systems II,    ; Hybrid Systems III,    ; Hybrid Sys- tems IV,    ; Hybrid Systems V,    ; Hybrid and R e al-Time Systems-HAR T'  ,    ; Hybrid Systems: Computation and Contr ol-HSCC'  ,    ; Hybrid Systems: Computation and Contr ol- HSCC' ,   ; Hybrid Systems: Computation and Contr ol-HSCC' 000,  000).   Mo dels of Hybrid Systems There are sev eral standard mo dels for con tin uous dynamic systems and discrete dy anmics systems. a a Throughout the remainder of the pap er, the terms c on- tinuous and discr ete refer to the t yp es of input, output and In the con trol literature, it is common to mo del h ybrid systems as the comp osition of con tin uous and discrete dynamic systems in terconnected b y discrete and con tin uous signals (An tsaklis et al.,    ). Blo c k diagrams can then b e used to repre- sen t h ybrid dynamic systems with sp ecial blo c ks to mak e con v ersions b et w een discrete-v alued and con tin uous-v alued signals (Krogh,    ). Another approac h to mo deling the discrete asp ects of a h y- brid system is to in tro duce logical (in teger) v ari- ables in expressions de ning constrain ts on the system b eha vior (Bemp orad and Morari,   ). This approac h has b ecome p opular in the pro- cess con trol comm unit y where discrete-time mo d- els are used in mo del predictiv e con trol (MPC) al- gorithms. In the computer science literature, con- tin uous dynamics are t ypically em b edded in the discrete states of the mo del, leading to the so- called h ybrid automaton (Henzinger,    ; Alur et al.,    ). The most appropriate mo del to use for a h y- brid system dep ends on the application con text and the to ols that will b e used for analysis and design. Systems in whic h the con tin uous dy an- mics dominate and discrete v ariables represen t relativ ely simple mo de-switc hing are most often mo deled using the con trol-theoretic blo c k diagram approac h. If the con tin uous dynamics are ex- tremely simple, suc h as pure in tegrators represen t- ing timers, and the discrete-state transition struc- ture dominates, the h ybrid automata framew ork is most natural. The follo wing sections describ e re- searc h directions for analysis and computer to ols that re ect the t w o mo deling p ersp ectiv es.   Con trol-Theoretic Concepts Con trol theorists ha v e studied v arious asp ects of h ybrid systems for man y y ears, although the name has b ecome p opular only recen tly (see, for ex- ample, (Witsenhausen,     )). One principal theme of the con trol researc h has b een to ex- tend de nitions and conditions for stabilit y of state v ariables used to describ e a system. As with con tin- uous and discrete dynamic systems, h ybrid systems can b e describ ed in discrete time or con tin uous time. 1 con tin uous systems to the h ybrid system con- text (Branic ky ,    ; Y e et al.,    ). P artic- ularly in teresting results ha v e b een obtained for piecewise linear systems using concepts from Ly- puno v stabilit y theory com bined with computa- tional metho ds based on linear matrix inequali- ties (Johansson and Ran tzer,    ; P ettersson and Lennartson,  000). New results ha v e also b een ob- tained on the stabilit y of nonlinear systems using discon tin uous feedbac k (Lib erzon,  000). Hybrid sytems pro vide a ric h con text for de ning v arious t yp es of con trol problems. One theme of the researc h on con trol in h ybrid systems has b een to build on results in the theory of dis- crete ev en t systems (Cury et al.,    ; Raisc h and O'Y oung,    ). In this w ork, the con troller is a purely discrete-state system, with discrete-v alued in terfaces to the h ybrid dynamic system. This is the situation often encoun tered in industrial con- trol systems, suc h as safet y con trollers for pro- cesses and discrete parts man ufacturing systems; that is, an y application in whic h a programmable logic con trollers (PLC) can b e emplo y ed. Sev- eral pap ers ha v e b een published on the syn the- sis of suc h sup ervisory con trollers for h ybrid dy- namic systems using the basic approac h of rst appro ximating the input-output b eha vior of the h ybrid dynamic system with a discrete-state sys- tem (Ch utinan and Krogh,  000). Lemmon et al. pro vide a go o d surv ey of researc h on con trol syn- thesis for h ybrid systems in (Lemmon et al.,   ).   The Computer Science P ersp ectiv e One of the most in teresting and stim ulating as- p ects of the recen t researc h activit y in h ybrid sys- tems is that the comm unit y of researc hers is it- self h ybrid, in v olving computer scien tists as w ell as con trol theorists. Recognizing that comput- ers often in teract with con tin uous dynamic sys- tems, computer scien tists ha v e b een activ ely pur- suing metho ds for extending their to ols to ad- dress h ybrid system problems. Most of this re- searc h has b een pursued in the con text of for- mal v eri cation using either mo del c hec king (Alur et al.,    ; Henzinger, Ho and W ong-T oi,    ) or theorem pro ving (Manna and Sipma,    ). Among the signi can t adv ances made from the computer science p ersp ectiv e are the exten- siv e results on the decidabilit y of v eri cation problems for v arious classes of h ybrid systems (Henzinger, Kopk e, Puri and V araiy a,    ; Laf- ferriere et al.,   ; Miller,  000). It is no w w ell kno wn that the in tro duction of v ery simple con tin- uous dynamics in a h ybrid automoton mo del can mak e v eri cation problems undecidable. These re- sults ha v e made it clear that one should not ex- p ect to o m uc h when b uil di ng computer to ols for analyzing h ybrid systems. They ha v e also encour- aged con trol theorists in terested in h ybrid systems to b ecome familiar with man y imp ortan t concepts from computer science.   Computer T o ols for Hybrid Systems Sev eral v endors of commercial sim ulation pac k- ages no w supp ort mo deling and sim ulation of h y- brid dynamic systems. Detecting ev en ts based on the ev olution of con tin uous dynamics and in te- grating the con tin uous dynamics correctly is the k ey issue in the sim ulation of h ybrid systems. F or v eri cation of h ybrid systems, sev eral researc h groups ha v e in tro duced soft w are pac k ages that can b e do wnloaded. These pac k ages represen t the state of the art in h ybrid systems researc h. A go o d resource for up-to-date information on h ybrid sys- tems soft w are, as w ell as other h ybrid systems information, is the w ebpage of the IEEE T ec h- nical Committee on Hybrid Dynamical Systems, http://www.nd.ed u/ lemmon/hybrid/.   Directions for F uture Researc h The eld of h ybrid systems has gro wn tremen- dously in the last few y ears. A searc h of the IN- SPEC database of scien ti c and tec hnical jour- nals using the k ey w ords \h ybrid systems" and \con trol" yielded  ,0   records! Consequen tly , it is imp ossible to predict where all the researc h is headed. Nev ertheless, one can iden tify some k ey issues that m ust b e addressed b y future re- searc h if the activit y in this eld is to ha v e sig- ni can t impact on engineering practice. The plenary presen tation fo cuses on t w o of these is- sues: the relationship of h ybrid systems researc h to to ols for computer-aided design and analy- sis of soft w are for em b edded con trollers; and the fundamen tal problem of computing reac habil- it y and attainabilit y sets for con tin uous dynamic systems. Recen t researc h on the latter prob- lem is rep orted in the follo wing references (Puri et al.,    ; Dang and Maler,    ; Ch utinan and Krogh,    ; Preu ig et al.,   ; Botc hk arev and T ripakis,  000; Greenstreet and Mitc hell,   ). References Alur, R., Courcoub etis, C., Henzinger, T. and P o, P .-H. (   ). Hybrid automata: an algorith- mic approac h to the sp eci cation and v eri- cation of h ybrid systems, Hybrid Systems, n um b er     in L e ctur e Notes in Computer Scienc e, Springer-V erlag. Alur, R., Henzinger, T. and Ho, P .-H. (   ). Automatic sym b olic v eri cation of em b edded systems, IEEE T r ans. on Softwar e Engine er- ing   ( ):    { 0 . An tsaklis, P ., Stiv er, J. and Lemmon, M. (   ). Hybrid system mo deling and autonomous 2</data>
  <data key="d5">2000/164.pdf</data>
</node>
